🇧🇷 É triste, não deu mais uma vez… o Brasil perde pra a Croácia e é desqualificado da copa do mundo. 

Pra mim, o mais triste é saber que trazer essa copa para o Brasil seria um momento de distração e felicidade para o povo brasileiro durante um momento tão complicado da nossa política, onde nossa população está tão dividida e com tantos problemas. Mas que mesmo com todos os problemas, durante a copa colocamos as divergências de lado e torcemos juntos com o mesmo objetivo. 
E eu, como atleta, sei da frustração de todos esses atletas que se prepararam e se dedicaram tanto com um objetivo, e de ver esse sonho ficando cada vez mais longe. Eu sei a dor que é tentar representar o seu país da melhor forma possível e não conseguir o resultado esperado, machuca, incomoda, mais do que se você não estivesse vestindo a verde e amarela. Então quando vejo nossos atletas no gramado, desacreditados, chorando… eu choro junto. 

O importante agora é que nós possamos perceber que da mesma forma que estávamos unidos para celebrar, precisamos estar unidos nas diferenças. É nunca desistir e seguir com esse sonho, seja lá qual ele for, vivo dentro de cada um de nós. 

Pra mim não tem nada mais lindo do que ver o meu país unido, torcendo, feliz e celebrando. Espero poder ver isso acontecendo todos os dias, e não só daqui a 4 anos. 

❤️🇧🇷🥇

🇺🇸 Some know me as a Paralympic tennis player, others as a gym rat, and still others as a marketing girl. But not many people know that my journey started as a swimmer. At the age of 10, I was introduced Paralympic sports through swimming and, to my surprise I did pretty good at it. I competed in many national competitions and even participated in the 2008 IWAS Jr. in New Jersey, where I returned with three medals. 
However, when I came back from the IWAS, I took a leap of faith and switched to tennis, which became my true passion. And, as you know, the rest is history.

My message to you is to take a chance and chase your dreams. The journey may be rough, but the reward is worth it. Stay active, stay motivated, and never stop exploring new opportunities. 💪🏻

🇧🇷 Alguns me conhecem como a tenista paralímpica, outros como a louca da academia e ainda outros como a menina do marketing. Mas poucas pessoas sabem que minha jornada começou como nadadora. Aos 10 anos, fui apresentada ao esporte paralímpico através da natação e, para minha surpresa, eu me dei muito bem nisso. Competi em muitas competições nacionais e até participei da IWAS Jr de 2008 em Nova Jersey, de onde eu voltei com três medalhas.

Today, I felt like sharing something with you guys. One of the questions I get the most is, "Where do you get your motivation from? Why do you do everything you do, and what for?" The truth is that my fuel is my family, my desire to make them proud, and represent them through everything I do.

Two years later, he passed away from pneumonia on his birthday while visiting me.
My mom and dad did everything they could to keep me doing what I loved. My mom would get up at 6 am to catch a bus with me that wasn't accessible to take me to practice. She had to carry me on her lap up and down the stairs, disassemble my chair, and carry it up afterwards. We had a lot of problems with bus drivers and people with prejudice riding the buses. Not to mention, it took a toll on her back to this day. She also couldn’t get a job because she needed to take me everywhere. My dad would skip his lunchtime from work to drive back home and pick me up to drop me at practice and get back to work right after. He would go around trying to get financial help to cover my travel expenses so I could keep playing.
My grandma was my biggest fan. She was there cheering for me when Renan told me I'd be a champion. She was always encouraging me, always telling me how much she loved and missed me. She would call me her daughter and always say that she believed in me. She passed earlier this month.
My aunts and uncles always took encouraged me and cheered me on. They all got together with the family and my friends, and sent me these pictures and messages before my debut in Rio. Even though they couldn't be there to watch me, they made sure to be present and support me.
So, I do it for them, the ones in heaven and the ones here. I do it to make them proud. I do it because they make me strong. They taught me how to be, because they believe in me and made me believe in myself.

Tomorrow is too late… what is stopping you from starting NOW?

🇺🇸 This is me trying a blade for the first time. I started using my prosthetic legs again not too long ago, but this was a whole different experience. The feeling was nothing like what I’m used to, and adjusting to the different knee and the bouncy feel of the blade was definitely challenging. So, my form may not look the best, but it was one of the coolest experiences I’ve ever had.

After that, I caught myself realizing that even though I’ve been involved in adaptive sports for over 16 years, I still get to experience something for the first time every year that I volunteer at the Angel City Games... and what an incredible experience it is!

Thank you @angelcitysports and @ottobock for making this possible and accessible to those like me who never had access to it but always wanted to try. I also want to thank @phprosthetics for their amazing staff. They truly went above and beyond to ensure that, despite the challenges of my unique amputation, I had the chance to try the blade.

And y’all can rest assured, one day I’ll have my own blade, and you’ll see me running.

🇧🇷 Essa sou eu experimentando uma lâmina pela primeira vez. Eu comecei a usar minhas próteses novamente não faz muito tempo, mas essa foi uma experiência completamente nova. A sensação nem se compara, e me adaptar ao joelho novo foi definitivamente desafiador. Então, minha caminhada pode não ser a melhor, mas foi uma das experiências mais legais que eu já tive.

Depois disso, me peguei pensando que, mesmo estando envolvida em esportes adaptados há mais de 16 anos, eu ainda acabo vivenciando algo pela primeira vez todo ano que eu sou voluntária no Angel City Games...

Obrigada ao @angelcitysports e @ottobock por fazerem isso possível e acessível para pessoas que como eu, que nunca tiveram a oportunidade de experimentar a lâmina, mas sempre quiseram. Também quero agradecer à equipe incrível da @phprosthetics. Eles se esforçaram ao máximo para garantir que, apesar dos desafios da minha amputação única, eu tivesse a chance de tentar.

🇺🇸 So, I haven’t been going to the gym or dieting for the past two weeks because of a couple of different reasons. One of them was that I was volunteering at the Angel City Games and didn’t have enough time or energy afterwards. Then I went on a last minute trip and got and Airbnb with a garage gym. So I decided to start exercising again right then and right there.

Getting back into the gym routine is tough. With higher BF, and less stamina and endurance. Plus, the garage was extremely hot. But that’s the whole point: to keep going even when you’re tired, sad, or whatever it is, and your body tells you to stop. What I love about the gym is those moments when your body wants to quit, but you push your mind to be stronger and keep going.

🇧🇷 Nas últimas duas semanas, eu não tenho ido à academia ou fazendo dieta por várias razões diferentes. Uma delas foi que eu estava fazendo trabalho voluntário nos Angel City Games e não tinha tempo suficiente nem energia depois. Depois disso, eu tive que fazer uma viagem de última hora e reservei um Airbnb com uma academia na garagem. Então, decidi começar a me exercitar naquele exato momento.

Retomar a rotina da academia é difícil. Com um índice de gordura corporal mais alto e menos resistência. Além disso, fazia MUITO calor na garagem. Mas esse é o ponto: continuar mesmo quando você está cansada, triste, ou seja o que for, e seu corpo pedindo para parar. O que eu amo na academia são aqueles momentos em que o seu corpo quer desistir, mas você se esforça mentalmente para ser mais forte e continuar.

🇺🇸 Taking it one step at a time, my fitness journey has not only brought mental and physical benefits, but it's also been a game-changer for my daily life. Loosing weight, gaining strength, and improving my cardio have all played a role in making walking with my prosthetic legs MUCH easier. I used to struggle after just a few steps, feeling exhausted and discouraged. Now, with the progress I've made, I'm able to walk much farther and even incorporate my prosthetic legs into my workout routines for an extra boost and be able to hit areas of the body that are harder to work while sitting. 🦿🦾 

🇧🇷 Dando um passo de cada vez, minha jornada fitness não só trouxe benefícios mentais e físicos, mas também mudou minha vida diária. A perda de peso, o ganho de força e a melhora da minha capacidade cardiorrespiratória contribuíram para tornar a caminhada com minhas próteses MUITO mais fácil. Eu costumava ter dificuldades depois de dar apenas alguns passos, me sentia exausta e desanimada. Agora, com o progresso que eu tive, posso andar muito mais longe e até incorporar as próteses nas minhas rotinas de treino para poder atingir áreas do corpo que são mais difíceis de trabalhar quando sentada. 🦿🦾

Creating @madapparel.us is one of my proudest moments yet. I had just gone to the gym at night, had a great workout, returned home, and went to sleep. That day, for the first time in a very long time, I dreamt. In that dream, I saw myself creating this shirt that said "#NOLEGDAYS" on it, with the word "LEG" scratched out and a handwritten "OFF" added afterwards, transforming it into "#NODAYSOFF." I woke up and that's all I could think about.

I work with graphic design, so I decided to bring that vision to life and see how it looked. When I finished, it resonated with me deeply, taking me into a creative frenzy. In three days, I ended up developing my entire brand by myself, including a name, a logo, a slogan, securing the domain, building the entire website, creating various designs, sourcing high-quality materials and clothing, establishing a presence on social media, designing posts, setting up the Instagram and Etsy shops, crafting the brand's mission statement, and more. Yes, all of this in just three days, driven by my obsession, often staying up until 5 am.

This happened because I was genuinely excited and passionate about it, in a way I hadn't felt in a while. I simply wanted to share my message in a tangible way that people could wear, feel, and be reminded of wherever they went. Wearing @madapparel.us would serve as a constant reminder of their capabilities and the daily battles they fight for.

Many people ask me how I manage to stay motivated to work out and give my all every day. The truth is, I'm not motivated most days. However, I've built a strong system and routine, lead by clear goals, that transformed me into a very disciplined person. Discipline outlasts motivation every time. So, the message of @madapparel.us is that motivation fades, but discipline endures. It emphasizes that we shouldn't use excuses or disabilities as a reason to quit. Instead, we should change the narrative. From #NOLEGDAYS to #NODAYSOFF, we refuse to let self-imposed limits hold us back.

🦿 For those who were curious, I do have prosthetic legs and this is how I put them on.

I’ve been trying to incorporate more cardio that I can do with them lately, and there are two main reasons for that:

1- Giving my arms and upper body a break: I usually aim to target each body part twice a week, which means four upper body days at the gym (Push x 2 & Pull x 2). On top of that, I rely on my arms for mobility, similar to how most use their legs. Even after leaving the gym, I have to use my arms for everything. So, to prevent  any upper body injuries and help with muscle recovery and growth, I’ve been avoiding my usual cardio options (rowing, assault bike, ropes, skierg...) and opting for exercises I can do with my prosthetic legs.

2- Paying more attention to my lower body, especially to promote hypertrophy in my lower abdomen and lower back. 
Sitting pretty much all your life makes it challenging to target those areas, making it a lot harder to get any definition at all. So I’m going to take advantage of the fact that I have the option to use my prosthetic legs to work on those areas more often. 

🦾 Fun fact: I can only use the spinning bike; regular stationary bikes don’t work very well for me. Since I don’t have one of my knees, the flywheel on the spinning bikes helps me keep the pace, and the foot cage keeps my prosthetics foot attached to the pedals.

Today marks 27 years since my accident, and I usually don't do posts like this, not because I dislike talking about it, but because to me, it feels like any other day. But I guess it’s not like any other day; it's a day that changed my life.

So, let me answer what everyone asks me every day: What happened?

I was born into a humble family, six people living in a two-bedroom apartment (picture 3). We didn’t have a car, so when I was 2 years old, I was at the bus stop with my mom. I was on her lap; she needed to put me standing in front of her for a moment to reach into her backpack for the tickets. But the bus that was coming was on high speed and lost control, going over the sidewalk and hitting me, launching me far away.
The driver realized what had just happened and tried to drive away, ending up running over my legs. I got stuck to the wheels as he continued to attempt to drive away. He then left running on foot, leaving the bus on top of me. I was still awake and responsive, calling for my mom. 

I had a 2% chance of survival. I had head trauma and injuries that resulted from being dragged on the asphalt, the doctors told my family the hospital wasn’t equipped for the situation.

My family didn’t have money to pay for my treatments and had to sell even the appliances to cover those costs… 

Still, here I am, somehow, for some reason. But hey, don’t pity me because of that! God just had bigger plans for me. I became a Paralympic tennis player, reaching the top 15 in the world, N°1 in my country, won a bunch of medals, travelled the whole world, learned different languages, gave a speech in the UN, was able to inspire and motivate so many people through my social media and assemblies, have an impact in my community, share my love for sports & fitness, and had SO MANY cool unbelievable life experiences.

The takeaway I want you to have is: No matter where you come from, what race, what financial situation, what struggles, what language you speak… if you want something enough, and you have God in your heart, you can get to unimaginable places

And call me crazy all you want, but I’m thankful for that day.

Be stronger than your excuses 🦾

When I first started working out, I considered my biceps my weakest point. Now, I feel like I’m slowly getting proud of my biceps development, and these are the exercises that are my current go-tos on pull day:

Warm-up: I always start with a light weight and high-reps set, usually aiming for at least 15 repetitions. During this time, I focus on maintaining good technique and tempo to really feel the stimulate mind muscle connection and promote blood flow to that area. This part is extremely important as we want to avoid injuries at all costs, SKIP LEG DAYS, NOT WARM UPS. 

My working sets: 
🦾 Incline dumbbell bicep curls: 3x12 (sometimes I’ll finish it with a drop set)
🦾 Preacher curls: 3x12
🦾 Cable rope hammer curls: 3x12

🏋🏻‍♀️ The weight:
Weight will be different for everyone, I usually don’t lift extremely heavy, as I’m not training for powerlifting, but for hypertrophy. So I always prioritize technique and time under tension. 

These workouts are usually done on my pull days, where I’ll also do back and abs exercises.

Quando comecei a malhar, eu considerava meus bíceps meu ponto fraco. Agora, sinto que estou aos poucos me orgulhando do meu desenvolvimento, e esses são os meus exercícios de bíceps atuais:

Aquecimento: sempre começo com um peso leve e uma série de repetições altas, geralmente visando pelo menos 15 repetições. Durante esse tempo, foco em manter boa técnica e ritmo para realmente sentir a conexão mente-músculo, e estimular e promover o fluxo sanguíneo para essa área.

Meus sets:
🦾 Rosca bíceps inclinado com halteres: 3x12 (às vezes finalizo com um drop set)

🦾 Rosca martelo com corda na polia: 3x12
